{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17522155","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17522155"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:42:10+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:42:10+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13810"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13810","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13810"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.02,0.79,0.12,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6427"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54824"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6427","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6427"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13810"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40355"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"759"},{"type":"tags","id":"1179"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12677"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12679"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14405"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44554"},{"type":"contributions","id":"49155"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54824","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/54824"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 50-year-old woman presents to her General Practice clinic with a two-month history of a painless lump in her right groin. She has noticed the lump is more prominent after prolonged standing and sometimes disappears when she lies down. Her medical history includes an excised basal cell carcinoma from her right leg two years ago. She does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, there is a soft, non-tender mass measuring 2 cm in diameter located inferolateral to the right pubic tubercle (Image). The lump is able to be reduced. No cough impulse is detected. There are no other palpable groin lumps and her peripheral pulses are normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Inguinal lymphadenopathy","Lipoma","Femoral hernia","Saphena varix","Femoral artery aneurysm"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe key features of this presentation are a painless, reducible groin lump in a middle-aged woman. The location inferolateral to the pubic tubercle is typical for a \u003Cstrong\u003Efemoral hernia\u003C/strong\u003E. Femoral hernias occur more commonly in women, possibly related to the wider pelvis. They are prone to strangulation and incarceration due to the narrow and rigid femoral canal, so urgent surgical referral is warranted even if the hernia is asymptomatic. Whilst the absence of a cough impulse in an abdominal wall hernia will often indicate incarceration or strangulation, this is not necessarily the case with femoral hernia, where the cough impulse is frequently absent, even in the uncomplicated hernia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInguinal lymphadenopathy\u003C/strong\u003E can cause groin lumps, but (depending on the cause) these are usually multiple, bilateral, tender, and non-reducible. The absence of palpable lymph nodes makes this diagnosis unlikely. Her history included a BCC from that leg, however BCC rarely (\u0026lt;0.05%) metastasises to regional nodes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Elipoma\u003C/strong\u003E is a benign fatty tumor that can occur anywhere in the body, including the groin. However, lipomas are typically not reducible and do not change size with position, unlike the lump described in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Esaphena varix\u003C/strong\u003E is a dilation of the saphenous vein that can occur at the saphenofemoral junction. It would be soft and reducible but would demonstrate a fluid thrill and may transilluminate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Efemoral artery aneurysm\u003C/strong\u003E would be pulsatile and may have an audible bruit. The normal peripheral pulses in this patient make an aneurysm unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Femoral hernias are more common in women and typically present as a painless groin lump below and lateral to the pubic tubercle.","Femoral hernias are at high risk of strangulation due to the narrow and rigid femoral canal.","Examination for cough impulse and reducibility can help differentiate hernias from other causes of groin lumps such as lymphadenopathy or femoral aneurysm."],"references":["Gandhi C, Mote D. Clinical, radiological and suprise diagnosis of femoral hernia. Internation Surgery Journal. 2023;10(7):1213:1215. Available at: https://www.ijsurgery.com/index.php/isj/article/view/9724","Goethals A, Azmat CE, Adams CT. Femoral Hernia. In: StatPearls [Online]. 2023. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK535449/","Gellatly M, Cruzval-O\u0027Reilly E, Mervak J, Mervak B. Metastatic basal cell carcinoma with atypical pattern on spread. Radiology Case Reports. 2020;15(12):2641-2644. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC7567923/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40355"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13810"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20753"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20753","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20753"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url